        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: use Object.hasOwn instead of in operator in usage bar translator",
        "body": "Related: #98466\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\n`key in table` checks the prototype chain, so `toString`/`valueOf`/`constructor` keys match `Object.prototype` instead of falling through.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nReplace `key in table` with `Object.hasOwn(table, key)` in alias lookup and case table lookup (2 lines).\n\n## User Impact\n\nFixes incorrect usage bar rendering when lookup keys coincide with prototype property names.\n\n## Evidence\n\nRuntime execution (Node 24, fix/in-operator-prototype branch):\n\n```\n$ node --experimental-strip-types\n> alias \"toString\" -> \"owned-value\" | expect: owned-value\n> map case \"toString\" -> \"fallback\" | expect: fallback\n> Object.hasOwn verified at runtime — prototype keys do not leak\n```\n\n- `translator.test.ts`: 15/15 passed ✅ (incl. 2 new regression tests for prototype key handling)",
        "branch": "fix/in-operator-prototype",
        "head_sha": "94a5d9b21588d9e711d7a04b8bfe0fbe5d4012d0",
        "author": "zhanglei99586",
